<Rating>1</Rating><user_id>117158240160472720782< /user_id><Text>I have copied and pasted this review from 2011 from Yelp. It is interesting for me to notice that Yelp filtered out this review and almost all the other 1 star reviews.

AVOID!

We drove here based on the fantastic YELP reviews, but now suspect these reviews were done by family and friends.

The employees were very nice and helpful, but misrepresented an item, though probably not intentionally. After getting it home we found that they sold us the wrong color. We had to repack it and drive it all the way back. Not a problem, mistakes happen. But they charged a 20% restocking fee for a cash and carry item (it was in stock, we didn't special order it) which was THEIR mistake.

In addition, the person handling the return was incredibly rude and somewhat violent. Because we did not want to agree to have the restocking fee subtracted from our refund, he started yelling and said he wasn't taking it back and actually pushed the item outside.

Because my husband and I do not live in California (we were there helping my son move) we were not at all familiar with furniture stores in that area. In searching online, we discovered Yelp reviews, and Far Below Retail has reviews that sounded almost too good to be true. Guess they were. As long as I am editing this review, I may as well include a paragraph from one of my emails to Christina:

"Christina, I don't enjoy writing a bad review. The misrepresentation (even if inadvertent) cost us valuable time, effort, and gasoline, but that is not why I wrote the review. We felt the restocking fee was unfair because it was a cash and carry item that was not special ordered, and the color was misrepresented., but that would still not be enough for me to write a bad review. I wrote the review after my husband and son came home visibly shaken from the return experience."

Do yourself a favor and avoid this unprofessional operation. Buy your furniture from a reputable dealer instead.</Text><Response>None</Response>< pics>

<Text>I just replaced front brake pads, front rotors, and did a brake-fluid flush on my car here. The facility is clean, modern, and well setup for people like me to try their hand at working on their own cars (I live in an apartment, I have no place to work on my car). They provide bays with lifts, air- and hand-tools, and nice workspace. Great value for the hourly rate, too. The owner, Dennis, was super helpful guiding me when I had questions. I needed him to show me how to perform a brake-fluid flush and he was patient, thorough, and articulate in his explanation of the procedure. Very helpful all around. It also wasn't super busy on the Saturday I was there (though the weather was a little on the warm side). Be a good neighbor when you're there (clean up after yourself; treat the tools, facility, staff, and fellow customers with respect; research the work you're doing on your car and have a good idea of how to do it before you go) and you'll have a great time, like I did. This was my first experience with Pit Row and I will absolutely return to do more work on my car.</Text>< Pictures>

<UserId.>102812192322952783623< /UserId.><name>Jaleh Afshar< /name><Gmap_id>0x808fca32fb463b01:0x99579a3858796966<//Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>
<user>115919404757088667990< /user>< Text>
I recently went to this place for the first time. Initially I really liked the facility and the overall set up. But when it came to check out, the entire experience was enough to make me not want to go back though. The way Dennis charges customers for time used struck a negative cord with me; it's a rip off that plays out in his favor. He charges in 30 minutes increments (which was not made clear when I got there). I did not appreciate finding out about this billing practice until after it was time for me to leave. Apparently the five minutes I went over the hour was enough justification for charging me for a full 30 minutes. Pit Row charges $35.00 per hour. Since I went over 5 minutes past the hour, this was justification for charging me an extra $20.00.

I previously have gone to Lifted Inc. over in Fremont a few times. I never had an issue with those guys charged me because it was based on what I actually used. Pit Row basically gets to pocket extra money from it's customers for time they didn't use. The only exception is if you stopped at exactly an hour, if you are 1 minute over, and now your getting charged for 1.5 hours.

I'd be more inclined to recommend Lifted Inc, over Pit Row. Lifted doesn't inflate my bill with time I did not get to use.<//Text>

<user>110075065636550135660< /user><user_name>emilio g< /user_name><date>1380558856259< /date>< rating>
5<//rating>
< review>
what a place!  for an hourly rate you get a lift and a chest of hand tools (SAE and metric, mostly Snap-On/Williams) that includes a couple pneumatic wrenches.  also included is access to specialty tools like spring compressors, brake piston compressors, or a tap and die set.  there are some heavy shop tools like a stand grinder & brush, drill press, and hydraulic press.  for an extra buck an hour you can use consumables like grease or the parts washer.  there aren't super crazy manufacturer-specific tools (bring your own) or a bunch of sheet metal and welding stuff (not that kinda shop), but there's plenty to do serious car work.

the folks that work there are very nice, extremely helpful, and accommodating to the realities of Murphy's Law.  i came down to do a thorough but routine brake job on a 2007 S4:  rotors, pads, lines, fluid flush, plus a fuel filter.  it's been a while since i've done a brake job, but it still _should_ have been routine...  but a combination of super-compact (and super-obnoxious) rear brakes with a few stuck and locally-unavailable bolts quadrupled the length of this job.  thankfully, they have a reasonable overnight rate for these problem projects and the manager provided advice and exceptional service that was critical to getting the job done right.  work carefully, take care of the tools and clean up after yourself, and they'll take great care of you.

this kind of shop is perfect if you live in an apartment, your house is unsuitable for car work (i have no garage and a gravel driveway, ugh), or you just need the joy of a lift.  you should have some experience with working on cars to save you time on the clock, for safety, and for proper tool use.  they have ALLDATA on site, which is a handy resource, but for complex jobs you should come in there well-researched and preferably with printed-out procedures.< /review>

<text>Update: Sorry to see them go out of business. My Altima's clutch needed replacement I got it done here. Half way thru I needed help and struck a deal with them to finish the job. Clutch parts were mine but the clutch was installed by them. 5 minutes after the job I noticed something leaking. They said it was water from AC compressor. After few more minutes of diagnosis it was determined transmission oil was leaking, literally dripping 2 drops a second. Dennis said because the part was mine workmanship was not covered by warranty. Honestly he struggled with the job, longer bolts went in wrong holes, forgot to replace the input shaft seal and screwed up the job and used the warranty policy  on a job that had not yet been delivered, meaning if he delivered it leak free and later I had leak the warranty policy applies. Basically he did not finish the job. Since he spent many hours I paid $150 more. Including parts it cost me $800. Money is one thing, my Altima is still gushing transmission oil, I just keep it in my garage. Guess what, it has been sitting in my garage for 5 years now. Still have the bad taste in my mouth and never went back to them.

After the analysis, I was partnered with Randy and have been working with him ever since. I train with him 1:1 once a week. He genuinely cares about his clients and their goals and is attentive, positive, professional, patient, knowledgeable, and most of all encouraging. < Text>
I got nothing but love for the P4L Fam! It was my first time ever doing personal training, and I'm glad I put my trust in them. From consultation, to my first day of training, to the small group classes, I've learned so much about fitness and my own body during this process. I don't know about you, but I've definitely walked into many gyms feeling intimidated and scared to ask questions about how to use machines or how to work out. But at P4L, they've created such a welcoming and friendly culture where you can just keep asking questions and learn about fitness that you can take with you years after. Bryant and Justine are super friendly, and they genuinely care about everyone who walks through those doors, which is why the culture matches exactly that. The coaches and staff are skilled, very knowledgeable, and know how to adapt the program to match your goals.

Shoutout to Brandon who manages the FiDi location. I trained with him for a year and a half and he's helped me work on my flexibility, balance, agility, as well as core strength since my goal for personal training was to get better at hiphop dance. I also really like how we can talk about all the new hiphop albums dropping, and basketball.<//Text>

< user>
117919222652300745693<//user>
<username>John O'Connor<//username><Date>1574375486217<//Date><Rating>5<//Rating>< Review>
Have been attending P4L (Runlab specifically) for a few months now, with the specific aim of getting back to running consistently and injury free. So far, only super positive things to say about the whole organisation.

I train with Randy who, to start with, is a passionate runner. Everything we do is focused on developing the mobility, activation and strength to directly help my running. I have been to other gyms and indicated similar goals, but find after a few weeks workouts stray back to generic gym sessions. P2L (and Run Lab specifically) is completely different - its all about conditioning for running. For me, the intial focus has been on getting the right movement patterns / mobility, and then progressively upping the intensity / weight. There is plenty of learning in this approach - from understanding running mechanics, your own body, and new routines / exercises - which I really like.

Randy is also willing to help design your workouts outside the gym that complement the one-on-one sessions, which for me is important to getting maximum value for my membership. For instance, when I have to travel, Randy will suggest specific gym sessions to keep progressing and avoid the stop-start habit. He is super diligent in following-up with any asks, and genuinely encouraging.

Everything else around the coaching is first rate. Really friendly and non-intimidating atmosphere, great equipment, and an responsive / flexible admin and billing support.</Review>

<Rating>5< /Rating>< Text>
I must say I was a bit unsure about this place because I couldn't figure out how could they have a perfect rating. Truth be told, they earned every single star.

I've gone to this place 3 times now and every time it's delicious. My friends and my husband have ordered different things off the menu and it's all been good.  I seem to always get the lamb gyro. It's loaded with tender lamb,  fresh veggies and a soft pita.  I'm a picky pasta salad eater and their's is the best!

The owners and staff are very professional and always curious. The restaurant and bathroom were immaculate.

If you haven't tried this place,  please do. You won't regret it.< /Text>

Third, I did not get the amount of time I was promised since she was running late and had to get to her next client. I would have understood if I was a walk-in and she had other appointments, but, when a customer is paying $85 (plus tip) for a service with an appointment made 2 weeks in advance, the technician should be mindful of it.

Worst company. My little brother was in an accident just yesterday and had to be rushed to the hospital. My mother had spoken to the police about that we had AAA insurance on the car and the police officer had told my mom that they will handle it and to be with my brother. The police had told this company about the AAA insurance, but didn’t charge the towing cost to the insurance. They are asking my mother... $300... $300 to tow the car.
